'''Arlen F. Gregorio''' (born 1931 in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]) is an [[American people|American]] [[attorney at law|attorney]], [[politician]] and [[mediation|commercial mediator]]. He was a member of the [[California State Senate]] from 1970 to 1978. As a Senator he chaired the Senate Health and Welfare Committee from 1979 to 1984 and was an elected member of the [[San Mateo County Board of Supervisors]] from 1979 to 1984. After leaving politics in 1985 he began a career in [[mediation]].

==Early life and education==
Gregorio was born in San Francisco in 1931<ref name="Gregorio 5"/> to a family who has lived in California for four generations.<ref name="Gregorio 5">{{cite web | url=http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/kt9d5nf5f1/entire_text/ | title=Inventory of the Arlen Gregorio Papers | publisher=''[[Online Archive of California]]'' | accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Gregorio 1">{{cite web | url=http://www.acctm.org/agregorio/ | title=Arlen Gregorio | publisher=''American College of Civil Trial Mediators'' | accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref> He grew up in the  [[Bernal Heights, San Francisco|Bernal Heights]] district until his family moved  to [[Burlingame, California]], where he attended [[Hoover School]], [[Burlingame High School (California)|Burlingame High School]] and the [[College of San Mateo]].<ref name="Gregorio 5"/> 
Gregorio served as a [[US Navy|U.S. Naval Air Officer]] for three years in the 1950s<ref name="Gregorio 5"/> receiving the [[China Service Medal]] for combat duty.<ref name="Gregorio 1"/> He received his bachelor's and law degrees from [[Stanford University]] in 1955.<ref name="Gregorio 1"/> He was an adjunct faculty member at Stanford University, [[Notre Dame University]] in Belmont, and [[College of San Mateo]].<ref name="Gregorio 3">{{cite web | url=http://members.calbar.ca.gov/fal/Member/Detail/26403 | title=State Bar of CA - Arlen Foster Gregorio | publisher=''[[State Bar of California]]'' | accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Gregorio 21">{{cite web | title=The Senate District 11 | publisher=''California Journal'' | date=December 1984 | pages=486}}</ref>

==Career==
Gregorio became a member of the [[California State Bar]] in 1955.<ref name="Gregorio 3"/>  He was a partner in general law practice from 1958 to 1970 and held the position of  Assistant City Attorney for [[San Bruno]] from 1962 to 1970.<ref name="Gregorio 3"/>  He also chaired the [[San Mateo County]] Democratic Central Committee from 1964 to 1970.<ref name="Gregorio 5"/><ref name="OH"/>

===Politics===
In 1970, he was elected to represent San Mateo County in the California State Senate.<ref name="OH web site"/> According to fellow Senator Alan Robbins, Gregorio "refused special-interest money" and "contributions over $100".<ref name="News 1">{{cite news | url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19931214&id=-ZQzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UTIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=6854,5774109 | title=Inmate Robbins' advice for lawmakers | work=[[The News-Sentinel]] | date=December 14, 1993 | agency=McClatchy News Service | accessdate=February 7, 2013 | author=Alan Robbins | pages=4}}</ref>  During his two terms in the Senate (1970 - 1978),<ref name="Gregorio 1"/> Gregorio authored laws dealing with legislation and [[campaign finance reform]], [[alcohol]] and [[drug abuse]], the [[arts]],<ref name="Gregorio 1"/> [[Natural environment|environment]], [[education]] and [[health]].<ref name="OH web site">{{cite web | url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/archives/oral-history/g.htm | title=Oral History Interview with Hon. Arlen F. Gregorio. | publisher=''[[California Secretary of State]]'' | year=1989 | accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Sac Bee">{{cite news | title=Gregorio Says Public Wants New Blood in Government | work=[[The Sacramento Bee]] | date=January 21, 1971 | author=Andrew Gale | pages=A6}}</ref><ref name="Gregorio 8">{{cite news | title=Gregorio Bill Becomes Law | work=Redwood City Tribune | date=September 30, 1977 | author= | pages=}}</ref><ref name="Gregorio 9">{{cite news | title=Gregorio Paid Price for Thumbing Nose at System | work=[[San Jose Mercury News]] | date=December 3, 1978 | pages=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Gregorio Regulatory Reform Bill Passes | work=[[San Mateo Times]] | date=August 24, 1976 | accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref>  He was chairman of the Senate Health and Welfare Committee<ref name="OH">{{cite book | title=Oral History Interview with Hon. Arlen F. Gregorio | publisher=''State Government Oral History Program of California'' | author=Arlen Gregorio, Ann Lage | pages=6<U+2013>9; 31<U+2013>34; 42, 47<U+2013>50, 53<U+2013>57; 153<U+2013>154}}</ref> from 1973 to 1978.<ref name="Gregorio 5"/> Gregorio had a particular interest in reforming campaign financing and the political process in general.<ref name="City Tribune">{{cite news | title=Gregorio's Years of Serving the People | work=Redwood City Tribune | date=February 11, 1977 | author=Roy Hurlbert | pages=}}</ref> His political reforms included allowing the public to attend state budget conference committee meetings and to access legislator committee voting results.<ref name="Gregorio 16">{{cite news | title=A Move for Open Primary | work=Peninsula Times Tribune | agency=January 19, 1984 | accessdate=February 7, 2013 | author=Mark Simons}}</ref>

In 1975, Gregorio challenged then Governor [[Edmund G. Brown Jr.]] to a debate after the Governor vetoed his "alcohol tax bill."<ref name="Lodi News">{{cite web | url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19751210&id=RxYzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MzIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=2312,2175378 | title=Liquor tax veto debate is proposed | publisher=Lodi News-Sentinel | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 30, 2013 | author=UPI | pages=page 3}}</ref> In 1976 he created legislation that would give members of the public the "voting majority on most regulatory boards."<ref name="Lodi July 1978">{{cite web | url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19780712&id=H-AzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bDIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=5535,991562 | title=Brown veto of bill expanding teacher board sharply rapped | publisher=Lodi News Sentinel | date=July 12, 1978 | accessdate=December 30, 2013 | author=UPI | pages=page 2}}</ref> Gregorio lost his November 1978 Senate bid by a margin of only 90 votes after a vote recount.<ref name="Gregorio 5"/> In 1979, he won a special election to the [[San Mateo County Board of Supervisors]] and was re-elected in 1980, serving through 1984.<ref name="Gregorio 20">{{cite web | title=Gregorio Gets Plenty of Respect As He Steps Down from the Supervisorial Post | publisher=''Peninsula Times Tribune'' | date=January 6, 1985 | author=Steve Taylor | pages=A1}}</ref> Gregorio's last political race was in 1984, when he left the Board of Supervisors to run again for the state Senate.<ref name="Gregorio 20"/><ref name="Join California">{{cite web | url=http://www.joincalifornia.com/candidate/2435 | title=Arlen F. Gregorio | publisher=Join California | date=Unknown date | accessdate=December 30, 2013 | author=Unknown author}}</ref> In that political contest, Gregorio and his opponent, [[Becky Morgan]], set a "new Senate campaign spending record" of $1.6 million.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-02-14/news/mn-2449_1_d-los-angeles | title=Unknown title | publisher=LA Times | date=February 14, 1985 | accessdate=December 30, 2013 | author=Gillam, Jerry}}</ref>

===Mediation===
After leaving politics, Gregorio began an attorney mediation practice in San Francisco in 1985.<ref name="Gregorio 1"/> He founded the non-profit, Peninsula Conflict Resolution Center in [[San Mateo, California]] in 1986.<ref name="Gregorio 1"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ghrmediation.com/html/mediators-arlen-gregorio.html | title=Arlen Gregorio | publisher=''GHR Mediation'' | accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> In 1989, he created the first law partnership that focused exclusively on the mediation of civil trial matters.<ref name="Gregorio 1"/> The firm is known as Gregorio, Haldeman & Rotman and is located in San Francisco.<ref name="Bio at GHR">{{cite web | url=http://www.ghrmediation.com/html/mediators-arlen-gregorio.html | title=Arlen Gregorio Bio | publisher=Gregorio, Haldeman & Rotman | date=Unknown | accessdate=January 1, 2014 | author=Unknown}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Gregorio learned the [[Transcendental Meditation technique]] after reading a [[Wall Street Journal]] article about it in 1971.<ref name="Gregorio 18">{{cite news | title=Capitol time out on TM | work=San Francisco Examiner | date=June 1974 | author=Dennis J. Opatrny}}</ref><ref name="Gregorio 19">{{cite news | title=Meditation Irons Furrowed Brows in State Legislative Halls | work=San Francisco Examiner | date=June 10, 1973 | author=Dennis J. Opatrny}}</ref> He appeared with [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]], [[Clint Eastwood]] and others on an episode of the [[Merv Griffin show]] in 1975.<ref name="Goldberg, Philip 2011 page 166">Goldberg, Philip (2011) Harmony Books, American Veda, page 166</ref> 

He has three sons by his first marriage and began his second marriage in 1980.<ref name="Gregorio 5"/><ref name="Gregorio 1"/>

